It\&amp;#039;s hard to objectively describe DJ Sigue Sigue Fabrique\&amp;#039;s lively mashup dj sets. They tend to float out of the style and form boundaries, creating a frivolous void while playing with the terms \&quot;clichÃƒÆ’?Ãƒâ€šÃ‚Â©\&quot;, \&quot;shift\&quot;, \&quot;error\&quot; and \&quot;deja-vu\&quot;. Perfectly synched rhythm patterns let the listeners enjoy themselves, until they are deliberately \&quot;shifted\&quot; by error.
Playfulness + break + heavy metal + punk + llektro = RoboDada
In addition to manipulating digital music files using dj software, he uses DIY style loops - often too much at a time - and vinyl records combined with Finalscratch.
He is also an active music producer under several aliases (actually creating non-existent bands with label mates using the moniker \&quot;The Festival of Non-Existent Bands\&quot;) and remixer, emphasizing the terms \&quot;deconstruction\&quot; and \&quot;shift\&quot; of pop music, for instance an underground cult hit/remix of ex-Soviet pop star Anne Veski\&amp;#039;s track (titled \&quot;Anne Pseudoveski - Aparaat\&quot;) plus remixes for estonian ska-pop-rock group \&quot;Soterios\&quot; (\&quot;Twisted Romance Fabrique\&amp;#039;s amiga_adult_riot rmx\&quot;) and myspace band \&quot;Ladies! Disaster\&quot; (to be released).
He is a founder of Robodada Records, conceptual record label living up to its name (www.robodada.com)

